<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/CAA9A40D-0226-4A4F-AC0D-D8299E30A1EF"><gtr:id>CAA9A40D-0226-4A4F-AC0D-D8299E30A1EF</gtr:id><gtr:name>Loughborough University</gtr:name><gtr:department>Electronic, Electrical &amp; Systems Enginee</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Loughborough University</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Loughborough</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Leicestershire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>LE11 3TU</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/CAA9A40D-0226-4A4F-AC0D-D8299E30A1EF"><gtr:id>CAA9A40D-0226-4A4F-AC0D-D8299E30A1EF</gtr:id><gtr:name>Loughborough University</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Loughborough University</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Loughborough</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Leicestershire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>LE11 3TU</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/96BBA4CB-5F91-49BE-89A1-DDC594975A58"><gtr:id>96BBA4CB-5F91-49BE-89A1-DDC594975A58</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Philip  Charles</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Eames</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=EP%2FD060214%2F3"><gtr:id>87E3AD92-9B1E-4DA3-9C9B-4F126432C183</gtr:id><gtr:title>Development of a Novel Tunnel-junction-free Concentrator Cell and its Evaluation for a Smart Windows Application</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>EP/D060214/3</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>We propose to develop a novel type of solar cell that will generate electricity from sunlight with efficiency above 30%. This is at least twice the efficiency of the cells currently used to power roadside signs and comparable with the highest efficiency tandem cells which power satellites in space. However, our cell offers many advantages over the tandem, in particular the absence of a tunnel-junction. This means they can cope with the large variations in the intensity and spectral content of sunlight on buildings and in the light-concentrating systems which reduce the cost of solar electricity. Our cell is particularly suited to an exciting new application - smart windows. These are double-glazed facades containing arrays of small plastic lenses which follow the sun's movement and focus sunlight onto small, unobtrusive solar cells. Direct sunlight is removed and the air-conditioning load reduced, while the smart windows provide combined heat and power (CHP) for the building. Even in London the electricity generated would power the office behind a south facing wall. The smart windows also allow glare-free diffuse sunlight into the room, which is ideal lighting for a computer screen. The cells will also be ideal for integration into hybrid CHP systems that provide electricity and hot water from concentrated sunlight with a natural gas backup. The new device incorporates the novel, nanostructured solar cell that the Imperial group have developed in collaboration with the EPSRC National Centre for III-V Technologies. The Centre for Sustainable Technologies will characterise the cell performance on prototype concentrators of the new UK company SolarStructure, which has recently been formed to manufacture smart windows.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C"><gtr:id>798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C</gtr:id><gtr:name>EPSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-05-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>71289</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Findings have formed the basis for research proposals submitted to Non-UK funding agencies by the RAs that worked on this project.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2015</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>5E32EC4A-A513-49ED-B838-6A552374FC9D</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes/><gtr:outcomeId>56d97839564a97.70570978</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Energy</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The optical, thermal and electrical performance of a smart window design that included high (30%) efficiency solar cells and an array of tracking Fresnel lenses was simulated for a range of different climates and locations. A small scale laboratory prototype system was produced. By concentrating the direct sunlight incident on the window onto the cells electricity was generated. By reducing the direct radiation passing through the window solar gains to the building interior were reduced and a significant reduction (up to 30%) in predicted cooling load was achieved. The diffuse solar radiation incident on the glazing passed into the room reducing the need for artificial lighting. Heat generated within the window was removed by controlled air flow.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The designed smart window system can provide electricity and heat and shading. The reduction in summer time cooling load achieved is significant. Prior to being suitable for commercialisation the economics of the system need to be proved with cost reductions realised. If systems can be produced at low cost with excellent long term durability in terms of the 2-D tracking system proven extensive use for commercial buildings in hot sunny climates would be attractive.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>A88C96CE-1F6B-4944-8A97-8755B1F8704B</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5460adb19a66e0.75067239</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Construction,Energy</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>2939481B-5117-4304-BFF0-541907D30282</gtr:id><gtr:title>Smart Windows: Optical Modelling and Evaluation</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/285f9ede4c3ba01963495774c103408a"><gtr:id>285f9ede4c3ba01963495774c103408a</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Philip  Charles Eames (Author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_703124270214015d60</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>49FE0063-2A3C-4FC3-B37B-7E19D31E95B3</gtr:id><gtr:title>Experimental characterisation of a Fresnel lens photovoltaic concentrating system</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Solar Energy</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/e1ae91a136cc1808e002adb45e242f69"><gtr:id>e1ae91a136cc1808e002adb45e242f69</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Wu Y</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>5460a2d40e82e5.71977570</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>4FBA70A2-9A27-446A-B4B2-B500A7104A68</gtr:id><gtr:title>Smart Windows: Optical and Thermal Performance Evaluation</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/5e64c08a426d17ad530ad93f90697744"><gtr:id>5e64c08a426d17ad530ad93f90697744</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Li Mei</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>r_8648400205cac79072</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>9E56B80F-4AC1-4D47-8538-8C566CACBEEC</gtr:id><gtr:title>SMART WINDOWS: OPTICAL AND THERMAL PERFORMANCE EVALUATION</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/285f9ede4c3ba01963495774c103408a"><gtr:id>285f9ede4c3ba01963495774c103408a</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Philip  Charles Eames (Author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_411452231214015cac</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>81D13BE8-A2DD-4389-AF8D-8540B5D03594</gtr:id><gtr:title>Smart Windows: Optical Modelling and Evaluation</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/bdbdace462e1a7204f601b16c61297c1"><gtr:id>bdbdace462e1a7204f601b16c61297c1</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Moshen Naqvi</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>r_4303543087cac791a8</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>CB5347A6-5B12-4FE2-AAC3-5BB37B1CEC2E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Smart windows: Thermal modelling and evaluation</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Solar Energy</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/1d2e46aa3b4a31d27bdba8526e930d3f"><gtr:id>1d2e46aa3b4a31d27bdba8526e930d3f</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Sabry M</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>5460a2d4344080.62742747</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">EP/D060214/3</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:projectHierarchy><gtr:parents><gtr:parent><gtr:id>AA432BC9-54EE-4571-A417-385E3748CF5F</gtr:id><gtr:grantRef>EP/D060214/1</gtr:grantRef><gtr:amount>165100.02</gtr:amount><gtr:start>2006-06-01</gtr:start><gtr:end>2006-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:children><gtr:child rel="Transfer"><gtr:id>2D3D6B8B-18F3-41A8-85E5-D57AA3